  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>In section 5, Sudbery notes (page 950):</html:p>
  <html:blockquote><html:p>
The structure algebra of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_{3}(\mathbb {K})]]></fr:tex> is obtained from (3.18), as for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H_{2}(\mathbb {K})]]></fr:tex>; factoring out the one-dimensional center, we obtain
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Str'}H_{3}(\mathbb {K}) = L_{3}'(\mathbb {K})\oplus \mathrm {Der}(\mathbb {K})=\mathbf {sl}(3,\mathbb {K})]]></fr:tex>
(this being a definition of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {sl}(3,\mathbb {K})]]></fr:tex> for non-associative <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {K}]]></fr:tex>). Equation (3.22) continues to hold for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[3\times 3]]></fr:tex> matrices; hence the Lie brakcets in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {sl}(3,\mathbb {K})]]></fr:tex> are also given by (5.3) and (5.4). When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {K}=\mathbb {O}]]></fr:tex>, this Lie algebra is a non-compact form of the exceptional Lie algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {E}_{6}]]></fr:tex>, the maximal compact subalgebra being <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {F}_{4}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p></html:blockquote>
</fr:mainmatter>
